HINT — Level 5: Kernel Module Escape

The Linux kernel can be extended at runtime by loading
kernel modules (LKMs). A process with CAP_SYS_MODULE can
call insmod to load a .ko file into the running kernel.

Code running inside a kernel module executes in kernel space —
outside any container, namespace, or cgroup boundary. It has
unrestricted access to the entire host system.

call_usermodehelper() is a kernel function that spawns a
userspace process as root on the host. A kernel module that
calls it executes arbitrary commands with full host privileges
the moment it is loaded, regardless of what container you are in.

Build the module. Load it.
